30:23.079 --> 30:26.347
My mum taught me. She
can do it in 90 seconds.

30:26.349 --> 30:28.314
Here.

30:28.316 --> 30:30.717
She sounds like fun.

30:30.719 --> 30:33.488
If you think it's fun being a kid.

30:37.092 --> 30:39.292
Where's your mum?

30:39.294 --> 30:41.762
She left. What do I do first?

30:41.764 --> 30:44.667
Because of the Professor?

30:57.646 --> 31:01.247
He says the older I get,
the more I speak like her.

31:01.249 --> 31:05.787
You know, I can see her face,
but I have no memory of her voice.

31:07.023 --> 31:09.122
I wonder what she sounds like now,

31:09.124 --> 31:11.526
who she's talking to.

31:14.229 --> 31:16.664
You're not the only one who
gets treated like a child.

31:21.269 --> 31:24.138
LAWRENCE (narrating): <i>We pulled
all kinds of different scams,</i>

31:24.140 --> 31:26.139
<i>but what the Professor
really loved...</i>

31:26.141 --> 31:27.640
<i>was cards.</i>

31:27.642 --> 31:31.078
No one knows exactly,

31:31.080 --> 31:33.446
but it's believed that
cards were invented...

31:33.448 --> 31:36.516
somewhere in the seventh century...

31:36.518 --> 31:38.385
by the Chinese.

31:38.387 --> 31:40.188
LAWRENCE (narrating):
<i>What didn't we invent?</i>

31:50.599 --> 31:53.466
PROFESSOR: <i>Cards were brought
down the Silk Road to markets</i>

31:53.468 --> 31:56.171
<i>in Egypt and the Holy Land.</i>

32:00.642 --> 32:02.678
<i>Originally,</i>

32:03.711 --> 32:06.881
<i>they were used to
predict the future.</i>

32:10.218 --> 32:13.520
<i>In the 15th century, in Germany,</i>

32:13.522 --> 32:16.926
