spent 50 bucks on a shit record.

40:50.104 --> 40:52.106
Okay. What now?

40:55.610 --> 40:59.680
No fucking way.

41:07.789 --> 41:10.155
- Let's go over what you're going to say.
- Can we?

41:10.157 --> 41:13.660
Your boyfriend's dumped you.
You're upset, on the verge of tears.

41:13.662 --> 41:16.229
He gave you these records, but
now you want to get rid of them.

41:16.231 --> 41:17.863
Wipe the slate clean.

41:17.865 --> 41:21.233
- But when you get to...
- I couldn't only sell it for 50 bucks. I get it.

41:21.235 --> 41:23.035
What if he recognizes his own record?

41:23.037 --> 41:27.039
He won't. He'll get distracted by your...

41:27.041 --> 41:30.311
- My what?
- Outfit.

41:32.914 --> 41:34.948
- Don't forget to upsell.
- Lawrence, I got this.

41:34.950 --> 41:37.182
This guy's gonna pay up
big for his own record.

41:37.184 --> 41:38.785
(broken English) Top dollar.

41:38.787 --> 41:40.689
(bell dings)

41:45.160 --> 41:48.061
- Did you want to sell those?
- Yeah, sure.

41:48.063 --> 41:50.863
I'll give you 20 bucks for the lot.

41:50.865 --> 41:53.832
Wait! Thank God I found you.

41:53.834 --> 41:55.869
Sorry. These are my father's records.

41:55.871 --> 41:57.836
- That's my sister.
- Your sister?

41:57.838 --> 41:59.872
(whispers) She's adopted.

41:59.874 --> 42:01.575
Aaah!

42:03.711 --> 42:06.812
(broken English) Oh. Oh, Rory MacLachlan.

42:06.814 --> 42:08.314
So cool in Japan.

42:08.316 --> 42:10.716
No, he's not. I looked it up.

42:10.718 --> 42:13.086
(slurping)

42:13.088 --> 42:15.954
LAWRENCE (narrating): <i>The mark of a
good con is not how much money you make.</i>

42:15.956 --> 42:18.325
<i>It's how clean you get away.</i>

42:20.996 --> 42:24.064
Well, you broke it, you bought it.

42:24.066 --> 42:27.468
The old china. (slurping)

42:30.037 --> 42:33.740
<i>♪ Just as long as you
gonna get what you need ♪</i>

42:33.742 --> 42:36.075
- It would have worked.
- Don't worry about it.

42:36.077 --> 42:39.044
- I've seen worse.
- You've seen worse?

42:39.046 --> 42:40.979
No, not really. (laughing)

42:40.981 --> 42:42.648
Oh, my God.

42:42.650 --> 42:47.954
PROFESSOR: Don't despair, Lawrence,
my boy. You've made a great beginning.

42:47.956 --> 42:50.256
Oh, my first con.

42:50.258 --> 42:52.258
(continues, faint)

42:52.260 --> 42:55.961
<i>♪
Ooh-ooh-ooh ♪</i>

42:55.963 --> 42:58.566
<i>♪ Ooh-ooh-ooh ♪♪</i>

43:00.102 --> 43:02.267
LAWRENCE (narrating): <i>The
Professor loved to play poker.</i>

43:02.269 --> 43:05.437
<i>Even more, he loved
to cheat at poker.</i>

43:05.439 --> 43:10.008
<i>After all, poker is a game
designed to be played by liars.</i>

43:10.010 --> 43:15.048
The ultimate form of the lie is the bluff.

43:15.050 --> 43:19.318
Bluffing turns a game of chance

43:19.320 --> 43:21.789
into a game of skill.

43:27.329 --> 43:30.930
LAWRENCE (narrating): <i>But that's not the
only reason the Professor loved poker.</i>

43:30.932 --> 43:36.102
<i>As far as I could tell, it was across
a poker table that he met... her.</i>

43:36.104 --> 43:40.039
WOMAN: <i>♪ In my
foolish lover's game ♪</i>

43:40.041 --> 43:43.276
<i>She was a small-time
cheat, a peeker.</i>

43:43.278 --> 43:45.812
<i>She used shiners, tiny mirrors,</i>

43:45.814 --> 43:49.284
<i>to get a glimpse of the
cards as they were dealt.</i>

43:52.086 --> 43:54.922
<i>It's easy to spot if you
know what to look for.</i>

43:55.990 --> 43:58.258
<i>The Professor did
know what to look for,</i>

43:58.260 --> 44:01.830
<i>but he also liked what he saw.</i>

44:04.532 --> 44:07.367
<i>The Professor was mucking back then,</i>

44:07.369 --> 44:10.305
<i>introducing foreign
cards into a game.</i>

44:11.872 --> 44:14.340
<i>He was good,</i>

44:14.342 --> 44:16.175
<i>but so was she.</i>

44:16.177 --> 44:19.211
<i>Or maybe he tipped his hand.</i>

44:19.213 --> 44:21.481
<i>They became partners.</i>

44:21.483 --> 44:23.883
<i>More than partners.</i>

44:23.885 --> 44:25.885
<i>And together, they became readers.</i>

44:25.887 --> 44:29.488
Readers use a marked deck.

44:29.490 --> 44:33.325
On the back of the cards are
tiny dots or hidden patterns.

44:33.327 --> 44:37.229
Readers switch the
honest deck for their own.

44:37.231 --> 44:40.534
This is called cooling the deck.

44:44.405 --> 44:48.173
LAWRENCE (narrating): <i>Together, they
could take on bigger rooms, higher stakes.</i>

44:48.175 --> 44:51.544
<i>But cooling the deck
is a dangerous game.</i>

44:51.546 --> 44:54.314
<i>If someone suspects another
player of being a reader,</i>

44:54.316 --> 44:57.886
<i>all he needs to do
is demand a new deck.</i>

45:04.025 --> 45:10.432
<i>♪ Take my breath away ♪</i>

45:13.901 --> 45:16.035
- <i>♪ Take my breath away ♪</i>
- <i>But they were good.</i>

45:16.037 --> 45:17.970
<i>They were very good.</i>

45:17.972 --> 45:20.240
<i>There's no encouragement
like success,</i>

45:20.242 --> 45:22.475
<i>and they wanted more.</i>

45:22.477 --> 45:24.913
- <i>Enter Riley.</i>
- <i>♪ Take my... ♪♪</i>

45:30.651 --> 45:34.389
(all laughing)

45:36.490 --> 45:40.559
<i>Riley was a great
cheat, a card mechanic.</i>

45:40.561 --> 45:43.162
<i>He was always looking for an angle,</i>

45:43.164 --> 45:47.369
<i>and he cheated at every opportunity.</i>

45:55.577 --> 45:59.680
<i>By the time Sarah was
born, it was over.</i>

46:01.249 --> 46:04.017
<i>Maybe he should have seen it coming.</i>

46:04.019 --> 46:07.421
<i>But you cannot cheat an honest man.</i>

46:33.581 --> 46:36.249
(snoring)

46:36.251 --> 46:39.486
SARAH (whispering): Hey, Lawrence.

47:08.383 --> 47:11.119
- Where did you get that?
- Out of your bag.

47:18.492 --> 47:20.861
Do as I do.

47:32.673 --> 47:35.376
- (coughing)
- (chuckles)

47:54.396 --> 47:56.398
(exhales)

48:04.139 --> 48:07.205
It's one of the oldest in the
book. Don't worry about it.

48:07.207 --> 48:10.110
I'm not my father. Keep your money.

48:11.345 --> 48:13.745
- Did you bring me in here to scam me?
- What else?

48:13.747 --> 48:16.149
(chuckles)

48:16.151 --> 48:19.619
- Do you have any friends?
- And what would I do with friends?

48:19.621 --> 48:22.120
- Normal people sometimes have some.
- Have you ever had a girlfriend?

48:22.122 --> 48:24.691
- Sure.
- Bullshit.

48:31.298 --> 48:33.599
(sighs)

48:33.601 --> 48:35.300
I've never had a girlfriend.

48:35.302 --> 48:38.738
(chuckles) I will drink to that.

48:38.740 --> 48:42.809
To no girlfriends.

48:42.811 --> 48:45.747
- To no boyfriends.
- To no fucking friends at all.

48:56.191 --> 48:58.256
My father has no friends.

48:58.258 --> 49:00.593
- What about me?
- (chuckles)

49:00.595 --> 49:04.097
Has the old fucker still not told you?

49:04.099 --> 49:06.798
(chuckles)

49:06.800 --> 49:09.203
(pouring liquid)

49:13.340 --> 49:16.108
(retches, groans)

49:16.110 --> 49:19.678
Oh, God.

49:19.680 --> 49:22.782
(retches)

49:22.784 --> 49:24.885
Okay, okay.

49:29.890 --> 49:32.827
(retches) Ah!

49:34.528 --> 49:38.599
♪♪ (traditional)

50:01.722 --> 50:06.225
LAWRENCE (narrating): <i>When something
looks too good to be true, it usually is.</i>

50:06.227 --> 50:08.294
<i>Lying to people was really fun,</i>

50:08.296 --> 50:11.696
<i>but being lied to, not so much.</i>

50:11.698 --> 50:14.533
- Forty.
- Correct.

50:14.535 --> 50:17.269
- I don't know, about 30.
- Ah, Lawrence!

50:17.271 --> 50:21.575
- Thirty-two.
- Yeah, that's good.

50:23.778 --> 50:28.213
- Nineteen.
- You're not concentrating.

50:28.215 --> 50:30.448
What am I doing here?

50:30.450 --> 50:32.350
You are studying the art.

50:32.352 --> 50:33.852
That's not what I mean.

50:33.854 --> 50:37.689
Why are we here? Where are we going?

50:37.691 --> 50:39.425
We're going to Melbourne.

50:39.427 --> 50:41.494
Melbourne? I don't want
to go back to Melbourne.

50:41.496 --> 50:43.296
What possible reason
could you have to go there?

50:43.298 --> 50:45.698
A card game.

50:45.700 --> 50:48.267
A big one.

50:48.269 --> 50:50.602
Every year for the past 50
years, a game's been played...

50:50.604 --> 50:53.372
in the same kitchen in Melbourne.

50:53.374 --> 50:55.240
The Cook's Game.

50:55.242 --> 50:59.445
<i>Once played by the head
chefs of fancy hotels,</i>

50:59.447 --> 51:02.347
<i>the Cook's Game is now
worth the kind of money</i>

51:02.349 --> 51:06.251
<i>that attracts serious gamblers</i>

51:06.253 --> 51:08.689
<i>and dangerous men.</i>

51:10.291 --> 51:14.492
<i>I don't intend to lose the
Cook's Game a second time.</i>

51:14.494 --> 51:17.296
It takes $10,000

51:17.298 --> 51:19.664
and the right connections to get a seat

51:19.666 --> 51:21.867
at the green felt.

51:21.869 --> 51:24.738
You aren't answering my question.

51:26.707 --> 51:31.376
It's called the Little
Red Riding Hood game.

51:31.378 --> 51:32.845
I'm the brass.

51:32.847 --> 51:35.013
If I win my deal,

51:35.015 --> 51:36.881
the lambs know I'm a mechanic.

51:36.883 --> 51:39.619
So the old Professor

51:39.621 --> 51:41.887
needs a secret partner.

51:41.889 --> 51:46.559
I send a basket of
goodies to grandma's house.

51:46.561 --> 51:49.296
I need a wolf in disguise.

51:51.032 --> 51:55.033
So all this time, you just
wanted someone for a card game.

51:55.035 --> 51:57.769
Did you think I was teaching you
out of the goodness of my heart?

51:57.771 --> 52:00.305
- And afterwards?
- You'll get your share.

52:00.307 --> 52:02.841
What you do with it is up to you.

52:02.843 --> 52:06.512
Look, you asked me why I
brought you here. I told you.

52:06.514 --> 52:09.314
But ask yourself,

52:09.316 --> 52:11.885
why are you still here?

52:13.720 --> 52:16.657
Because you love it.

52:18.026 --> 52:22.294
Lying, cheating.

52:22.296 --> 52:26.631
The gift of the grift is inside you.

52:26.633 --> 52:29.468
Always has been.

52:29.470 --> 52:32.070
Now I told you you could
leave whenever you wanted.

52:32.072 --> 52:34.707
And so you can.

52:34.709 --> 52:37.943
(chuckles) But you won't.

52:37.945 --> 52:39.981
Watch me.

52:41.715 --> 52:44.751
Lawrence, don't let him get to you.

52:47.854 --> 52:51.791
<i>(line ringing)</i>

52:51.793 --> 52:54.727
LAWRENCE (on answering machine): <i>Hi.
You've called Leo, Mai-Ling and Lawrence.</i>

52:54.729 --> 52:58.564
- <i>No one's home. Please leave a message.</i>
- <i>(beeps)</i>

52:58.566 --> 53:02.033
Hi, Mum. Hi, Dad. It's
Lawrence. Remember me?

53:02.035 --> 53:05.671
- (fireworks exploding)
- It's noisy here.

53:05.673 --> 53:09.008
I just want to tell you...

53:09.010 --> 53:12.077
(sighs) I just wanted to say...

53:12.079 --> 53:13.979
LAWRENCE (narrating): <i>But
the Professor was right.</i>

53:13.981 --> 53:16.084
(Chinese)

53:17.885 --> 53:20.854
<i>I did love it.</i>

53:51.052 --> 53:54.553
<i>Every businessman knows you
need money to make money.</i>

53:54.555 --> 53:58.890
<i>To get two seats in the
Cook's Game, we needed money.</i>

53:58.892 --> 54:00.526
<i>Lots of it.</i>

54:00.528 --> 54:02.430
<i>In a hurry.</i>

54:20.648 --> 54:23.117
Lawrence. Can you come here a sec?

54:32.626 --> 54:34.528
(sighs)

54:36.430 --> 54:39.900
- How old are you?
- Nineteen.

54:41.635 --> 54:43.035
Eighteen.

54:43.037 --> 54:45.104
I can tell when you're lying.

54:45.106 --> 54:48.476
(scoffs) Seventeen and a half.

54:51.746 --> 54:55.015
- You haven't touched a girl before, have you?
- Sure.

54:56.550 --> 54:59.952
What's my tell? A twitch? My voice? What?

54:59.954 --> 55:02.523
Do you really want to know?

55:12.633 --> 55:15.633
- Do you like me, Lawrence?
- No.

55:15.635 --> 55:17.836
And there's your tell.

55:17.838 --> 55:20.407
I didn't see anything.

55:21.541 --> 55:23.376
Let's see.

55:24.579 --> 55:26.579
You come from a leafy Melbourne suburb

55:26.581 --> 55:29.881
with nice cars and a public library.

55:29.883 --> 55:31.916
You're a mama's boy.

55:31.918 --> 55:35.053
Your father had such high hopes for you.

55:35.055 --> 55:38.823
What would he say if he could see you now?

55:38.825 --> 55:40.925
But what you really want to know

55:40.927 --> 55:43.896
is if a girl like me

55:43.898 --> 55:47.867
could ever be with a boy like you.

55:47.869 --> 55:52.937
Could you? I mean, do you like me?

55:52.939 --> 55:55.041
No.

55:58.178 --> 55:59.879
Aren't you gonna call my bluff?

55:59.881 --> 56:05.017
<i>♪ And follow your
own heart now ♪</i>

56:05.019 --> 56:09.021
<i>♪ Always ♪</i>

56:09.023 --> 56:13.158
<i>♪ I remember you ♪</i>

56:13.160 --> 56:17.062
<i>♪ Slow down ♪</i>

56:17.064 --> 56:20.935
<i>♪ And try to tell the truth ♪♪</i>

56:25.706 --> 56:28.242
I have a good poker face.

56:32.113 --> 56:34.613
You act angry when you're lonely,

56:34.615 --> 56:36.981
which is most of the time.

56:36.983 --> 56:40.251
You don't want to play the
Badger, but he told you to.

56:40.253 --> 56:42.854
Your mum left you when you were little.

56:42.856 --> 56:46.992
And one day... One day you'll
have the guts to leave too.

56:46.994 --> 56:49.229
But not yet.

56:54.135 --> 56:57.204
(sighs)

57:46.887 --> 57:50.155
It's only business.

57:50.157 --> 57:51.856
Come on.

57:51.858 --> 57:55.996
LAWRENCE (narrating): <i>The most lucrative
con we ever pulled was the Badger.</i>

57:57.331 --> 57:59.666
<i>Sarah played the Mack.</i>

58:08.675 --> 58:10.742
<i>The suckers were businessmen,</i>

58:10.744 --> 58:13.077
<i>married and in town for business.</i>

58:13.079 --> 58:15.782
<i>All kinds of business.</i>

58:23.356 --> 58:25.923
- Hit me.
- What?

58:25.925 --> 58:28.260
Hit me.

58:28.262 --> 58:30.162
(sighs)

58:30.164 --> 58:34.099
You fucking liar!

58:34.101 --> 58:37.936
- Don't call me a liar.
- I trusted you.

58:37.938 --> 58:40.872
So I lied to you. Big deal.

58:40.874 --> 58:45.445
- I thought you loved me.
- Grow up. People cheat.

59:04.898 --> 59:08.166
- Go back to the motel.
- What if you need help?

59:08.168 --> 59:11.604
Go back to the motel.

59:14.742 --> 59:17.443
LAWRENCE (narrating): <i>The Badger
followed the five steps of a con,</i>

59:17.445 --> 59:21.345
<i>but was different in
one important respect.</i>

59:21.347 --> 59:25.218
<i>In the Badger, the
suckers roped themselves.</i>

59:28.889 --> 59:30.356
Hey.

59:47.207 --> 59:50.341
LAWRENCE (narrating): <i>The Badger
doesn't rely on a sucker's greed.</i>

59:50.343 --> 59:54.782
<i>It plays on a different
instinct altogether.</i>

01:00:20.374 --> 01:00:23.508
You're in a hurry.

01:00:23.510 --> 01:00:26.779
You are... so beautiful.

01:00:27.981 --> 01:00:29.881
Do you have anything to drink?

01:00:29.883 --> 01:00:32.418
Uh, yeah. Yeah, sure.

01:01:17.064 --> 01:01:18.497
LAWRENCE (narrating): <i>When
the moment was right,</i>

01:01:18.499 --> 01:01:20.231
<i>the Professor would
barge into the room,</i>

01:01:20.233 --> 01:01:23.100
<i>claiming to be her father.</i>

01:01:23.102 --> 01:01:26.506
<i>The Badger was the one
time he told the truth.</i>

01:01:29.476 --> 01:01:31.075
Oh, no.

01:01:31.077 --> 01:01:33.579
<i>He'd tell some story
about how she was only 16,</i>

01:01:33.581 --> 01:01:38.383
<i>threaten to talk to his
family, his work, the press.</i>

01:01:38.385 --> 01:01:40.484
<i>And the sucker would always pay.</i>

01:01:40.486 --> 01:01:42.620
<i>Through the nose. Guaranteed.</i>

01:01:42.622 --> 01:01:44.258
Please.

01:01:54.367 --> 01:01:59.171
<i>But the worst thing about the
Badger was that it was so effective.</i>

01:01:59.173 --> 01:02:01.976
<i>We played it night after night.</i>

01:02:03.878 --> 01:02:06.445
<i>It's only business.</i>

01:02:06.447 --> 01:02:09.314
Share the risk, share the reward.

01:02:09.316 --> 01:02:11.252
Hmm.

01:02:17.090 --> 01:02:18.925
Dinnertime.

01:02:23.930 --> 01:02:26.497
- They grow up so quickly.
- Mmm.

01:02:26.499 --> 01:02:28.666
- Hello, Henry.
- Sarah, my dear.

01:02:28.668 --> 01:02:31.671
You look more like your mother every day.

01:02:32.972 --> 01:02:36.274
Lawrence, this is the Birdman.

01:02:36.276 --> 01:02:38.910
Hello.

01:02:38.912 --> 01:02:41.548
Are you sure you're ready
for this, Master Lawrence?

01:02:43.082 --> 01:02:45.485
- (chuckles)
- (chuckles)

01:02:48.088 --> 01:02:51.455
It's an international affair.
Elmsley's in again, and, um,

01:02:51.457 --> 01:02:54.992
some serious gambling junkie from Dubai.

01:02:54.994 --> 01:02:57.129
And then of course there's Riley.

01:02:57.131 --> 01:02:59.700
Now what about the, uh...

01:03:02.602 --> 01:03:05.706
Ah, let's eat.

01:03:17.985 --> 01:03:21.186
I'll do what I have to to get
you the cards that you need.

01:03:21.188 --> 01:03:24.488
Bet big on my deal, but
do not try being creative.

01:03:24.490 --> 01:03:28.327
For you, this is just
about good card playing.

01:03:28.329 --> 01:03:31.595
- So I've learned it all for nothing?
- They'll carve you up.

01:03:31.597 --> 01:03:35.869
At the end, it'll just be
you and me playing cards.

01:04:05.765 --> 01:04:08.635
(chattering)

01:04:12.740 --> 01:04:16.577
<i>♪♪ (dance)</i>

01:05:02.222 --> 01:05:04.356
[ Riley ] Beautiful.

01:05:04.358 --> 01:05:06.457
Isn't she?

01:05:06.459 --> 01:05:08.126
Who are you?

01:05:08.128 --> 01:05:10.662
You know who I am.

01:05:10.664 --> 01:05:13.832
And I know who you are.

01:05:13.834 --> 01:05:16.003
What do you want?

01:05:17.805 --> 01:05:19.973
A drink.

01:05:23.242 --> 01:05:27.278
You should stop following that old
fool around. It's got no future.

01:05:27.280 --> 01:05:30.548
- He's not a fool.
- He's always been a fool. Now he's an old one.

01:05:30.550 --> 01:05:32.818
- He'll beat you.
- (chuckling)

01:05:32.820 --> 01:05:36.153
Let me see. The Little
Red Riding Hood game?

01:05:36.155 --> 01:05:40.091
Perhaps a little cold tea in a hip flask?

01:05:40.093 --> 01:05:44.597
You play your little game.
I'm going to win anyway.

01:05:46.233 --> 01:05:48.901
<i>♪♪ (continues)</i>

01:05:50.169 --> 01:05:52.269
Ever been in love, Lawrence?

01:05:52.271 --> 01:05:53.405
No.

01:05:53.407 --> 01:05:56.374
(chuckles) I knew it.

01:05:56.376 --> 01:05:58.510
You have to work on that tell of yours.

01:05:58.512 --> 01:06:01.146
Don't worry. Your secret is safe with me.

01:06:01.148 --> 01:06:03.682
Love.

01:06:03.684 --> 01:06:06.787
It can make a man do things...

01:06:07.854 --> 01:06:10.754
things he will later regret.

01:06:10.756 --> 01:06:13.390
I don't think the Professor's
ever likely to forgive you.

01:06:13.392 --> 01:06:17.129
Sour old bastard got
what was coming to him.

01:06:17.131 --> 01:06:21.666
I'm talking about that little baby girl.

01:06:21.668 --> 01:06:24.037
My daughter.

01:06:27.441 --> 01:06:30.642
That's right.

01:06:30.644 --> 01:06:34.546
He hasn't told you that, has he?

01:06:34.548 --> 01:06:36.481
So, Lawrence,

01:06:36.483 --> 01:06:39.686
is my secret safe with you?

01:06:42.622 --> 01:06:44.957
May the best man win.

01:07:37.510 --> 01:07:39.510
Hey, stop!

01:07:39.512 --> 01:07:40.979
Lawrence? What are you doing here?

01:07:40.981 --> 01:07:44.416
You're in serious trouble. She's only 17.

01:07:44.418 --> 01:07:47.251
I'm afraid the only course of
action available to me, sir,

01:07:47.253 --> 01:07:48.852
is to contact your family.

01:07:48.854 --> 01:07:51.689
- No, Lawrence!
- That is, of course, unless

01:07:51.691 --> 01:07:54.894
you can think of another
way we can sort this out.

01:07:55.996 --> 01:07:57.629
(grunting)

01:07:57.631 --> 01:08:00.564
Get off him!

01:08:00.566 --> 01:08:01.966
(wheezes)

01:08:01.968 --> 01:08:04.401
LAWRENCE (narrating):
<i>It's all fun and games</i>

01:08:04.403 --> 01:08:08.340
<i>until someone loses an eye.</i>

01:08:08.342 --> 01:08:11.508
- Sarah...
- Shut up.

01:08:11.510 --> 01:08:13.613
Here.

01:08:22.723 --> 01:08:25.923
Nothing broken.

01:08:25.925 --> 01:08:29.394
I've never been in a fight
before. It really hurts.

01:08:29.395 --> 01:08:31.764
No shit.

01:08:37.970 --> 01:08:41.971
I was trying to be normal for one night.

01:08:41.974 --> 01:08:44.774
Sorry.

01:08:44.777 --> 01:08:47.611
You shouldn't have followed me.

01:08:47.613 --> 01:08:50.017
Just looking out for a friend.

01:08:51.684 --> 01:08:55.051
Lawrence, you're not my friend.

01:08:55.054 --> 01:08:58.689
I told you, we don't make
friends. It's not what we do.

01:08:58.692 --> 01:09:02.026
It's just Dad and me.

01:09:02.028 --> 01:09:04.330
He's... not...

01:09:06.966 --> 01:09:09.368
He's not here.

01:09:11.804 --> 01:09:14.340
You'll never be one of us.

01:09:15.709 --> 01:09:18.077
That's why I trust you.

01:09:23.582 --> 01:09:25.550
We can do this, Lawrence.

01:09:25.551 --> 01:09:27.920
We have to. We can leave him.

01:09:30.357 --> 01:09:32.359
Together.

01:09:48.974 --> 01:09:50.707
LAWRENCE (narrating): <i>I
know I look confident,</i>

01:09:50.710 --> 01:09:53.212
<i>but I got pretty good at pretending.</i>

01:09:55.048 --> 01:09:57.916
<i>But pretending is just another lie,</i>

01:09:57.918 --> 01:10:02.089
<i>and the Cook's Game
was the real thing.</i>

01:10:03.423 --> 01:10:05.492
(clears throat)

01:10:07.594 --> 01:10:09.961
You look great, Dad.

01:10:09.963 --> 01:10:11.732
Hmm.

01:10:13.400 --> 01:10:16.737
This is it, Lawrence,
my boy. (clears throat)

01:10:18.671 --> 01:10:21.006
I'll see you there.

01:10:22.075 --> 01:10:24.745
Do me proud.

01:10:31.384 --> 01:10:34.186
(door opens, closes)

01:10:45.098 --> 01:10:48.565
Don't move your eyes to the
right when you're bluffing.

01:10:48.567 --> 01:10:51.770
That's my tell? It's that obvious?

01:10:51.772 --> 01:10:53.605
Why couldn't I see it?

01:10:53.607 --> 01:10:56.443
Think about it.

01:10:58.778 --> 01:11:02.314
(chuckles) You can't see
your eyes moving in a mirror.

01:11:18.497 --> 01:11:22.167
Time to go, Hamlet.

01:11:22.169 --> 01:11:24.135
(sighs)

01:11:24.137 --> 01:11:27.407
<i>♪ Ah, what up, dog? ♪</i>

01:11:29.142 --> 01:11:31.912
<i>♪ Ooh, yeah, uh ♪</i>

01:11:34.981 --> 01:11:37.449
<i>♪ They say these songs
ain't the style no more ♪</i>

01:11:37.451 --> 01:11:41.188
<i>♪ When these kids go wild,
man, I ain't so sure ♪</i>

01:11:42.455 --> 01:11:45.023
<i>♪ Yeah, uh, check it out, uh ♪</i>

01:11:45.025 --> 01:11:47.458
<i>♪ They told me live
within your means, kid ♪</i>

01:11:47.460 --> 01:11:50.028
<i>♪ I don't know what that
means, man I dream big ♪</i>

01:11:50.030 --> 01:11:53.465
<i>♪ All day, I got these scenes where
we light the night up like gasoline ♪</i>

01:11:53.467 --> 01:11:56.133
<i>♪ Turning average into magic
like a pocketful of beans ♪</i>

01:11:56.135 --> 01:12:00.104
<i>♪ And it seems so simple But when I turn
the windows of my soul out the window ♪</i>

01:12:00.106 --> 01:12:01.773
<i>♪ Point 'em at my kinfolk ♪</i>

01:12:01.775 --> 01:12:04.508
- What name, young man?
- Jeremy Fong.

01:12:04.510 --> 01:12:06.877
Good luck tonight, Master Fong.

01:12:06.879 --> 01:12:09.847
This way, please.

01:12:09.849 --> 01:12:12.917
<i>♪ Baby hate the mirror, get
her pretty face all modified ♪</i>

01:12:12.919 --> 01:12:14.953
<i>♪ And I wish that I
could change it, love ♪</i>

01:12:14.955 --> 01:12:16.453
<i>♪ But ain't nobody
plans this stuff ♪</i>

01:12:16.455 --> 01:12:19.690
<i>♪ But it's gonna be all
right I'm crystal balling ♪</i>

01:12:19.692 --> 01:12:21.926
<i>♪ Don't worry about that shit
We'll work it out in the morning ♪</i>

01:12:21.928 --> 01:12:23.560
<i>♪ Get your last call in ♪♪</i>

01:12:23.562 --> 01:12:26.230
This is Master Jeremy Fong.

01:12:26.232 --> 01:12:29.266
Oh, you're younger than I expected.

01:12:29.268 --> 01:12:32.504
Welcome to the game. Please, take a seat.

01:12:34.640 --> 01:12:38.176
I don't recognize you, kid.

01:12:38.178 --> 01:12:41.044
Where do you normally play?

01:12:41.046 --> 01:12:44.918
Shanghai. Macau, sometimes.
My father's casino.

01:12:46.052 --> 01:12:50.687
I like him. If the kid pays, the kid plays.

01:12:50.689 --> 01:12:53.224
Macau?

01:12:53.226 --> 01:12:54.993
(Chinese)

01:12:54.995 --> 01:12:58.031
Sorry. I don't speak Cantonese.

01:13:00.200 --> 01:13:02.202
Only Mandarin.

01:13:05.237 --> 01:13:07.539
(door opens)

01:13:09.942 --> 01:13:13.744
Gentlemen, some of you
may have met Mr. Riley.

01:13:13.746 --> 01:13:16.748
Two-time winner of the game.

01:13:16.750 --> 01:13:19.284
You've met Rashid.

01:13:19.286 --> 01:13:24.955
This is Alex Elmsley, Jeremy Fong and...

01:13:24.957 --> 01:13:28.959
Hello, Vernon. How's
that little girl of yours?

01:13:28.961 --> 01:13:31.962
Please, Mr. Riley. Keep it nice.

01:13:31.964 --> 01:13:35.233
All friends here, Alice.

01:13:35.235 --> 01:13:37.200
Now... (cracks knuckles)

01:13:37.202 --> 01:13:40.473
let's play some fucking cards.

01:14:00.693 --> 01:14:03.860
<i>♪ You ain't gonna
see me comin' ♪</i>

01:14:03.862 --> 01:14:05.462
<i>♪ Got a quick draw ♪</i>

01:14:05.464 --> 01:14:09.132
LAWRENCE (narrating): <i>Poker is a
game designed to be played by liars.</i>

01:14:09.134 --> 01:14:11.069
<i>But not all liars are equal.</i>

01:14:11.071 --> 01:14:13.904
What about you, Professor?

01:14:13.906 --> 01:14:16.841
Have you grown a pair?

01:14:16.843 --> 01:14:19.377
Two pair actually. (chuckles)

01:14:19.379 --> 01:14:22.779
LAWRENCE (narrating): <i>The
inexperienced pretends to have skill.</i>

01:14:22.781 --> 01:14:24.815
<i>The skillful pretends to be green.</i>

01:14:24.817 --> 01:14:26.751
Screw you, kid.

01:14:26.753 --> 01:14:29.153
<i>And so we control the cards.</i>

01:14:29.155 --> 01:14:33.526
<i>The only variables
are the other players.</i>

01:14:37.129 --> 01:14:39.698
Motherfucker!

01:14:41.367 --> 01:14:43.801
Something to remember me by.

01:14:43.803 --> 01:14:46.236
Riley!

01:14:46.238 --> 01:14:48.006
Get him out of here.

01:14:48.008 --> 01:14:52.810
<i>♪ You ain't gonna
see me comin' ♪</i>

01:14:52.812 --> 01:14:56.681
<i>♪ So take your best shot ♪♪</i>

01:14:56.683 --> 01:15:01.118
LAWRENCE (narrating): <i>Ladies and
gentlemen, the Little Red Riding Hood game.</i>

01:15:01.120 --> 01:15:03.287
<i>The Professor stacks his chips dirty</i>

01:15:03.289 --> 01:15:05.791
<i>to tell me Rashid's number is up.</i>

01:15:06.992 --> 01:15:09.927
<i>First, I signal what cards I have.</i>

01:15:09.929 --> 01:15:12.198
<i>This card is a queen.</i>

01:15:14.034 --> 01:15:18.002
<i>He goes rabbit-hunting in the
muck to get the cards we need.</i>

01:15:18.004 --> 01:15:21.873
<i>Then he goes south
to stack the deck.</i>

01:15:21.875 --> 01:15:24.909
<i>He false shuffles with a
push-through or an up-the-ladder</i>

01:15:24.911 --> 01:15:27.580
<i>so the deck stays stacked.</i>

01:15:28.781 --> 01:15:31.382
<i>He crimps the bottom card
before he gives the deck</i>

01:15:31.384 --> 01:15:34.154
<i>to the next player to cut.</i>

01:15:36.822 --> 01:15:40.325
<i>And a classic pass gets
the cards back in order.</i>

01:15:49.768 --> 01:15:51.935
(clears throat)

01:15:51.937 --> 01:15:55.607
<i>With the cowboys we dealt
him, he has to take the bait.</i>

01:16:10.255 --> 01:16:13.356
<i>The flop turns both
pairs into trips.</i>

01:16:13.358 --> 01:16:16.159
<i>And right now, his three kings</i>

01:16:16.161 --> 01:16:18.395
<i>beat my three queens.</i>

01:16:18.397 --> 01:16:22.735
<i>Three kings... the
Christmas special.</i>

01:16:28.974 --> 01:16:32.409
<i>The Professor bottom
deals, and there she is.</i>

01:16:32.411 --> 01:16:35.512
<i>Rashid's money card.</i>

01:16:35.514 --> 01:16:39.283
<i>Now he has the boat.
Kings over queens.</i>

01:16:39.285 --> 01:16:42.255
<i>Almost nothing beats a full house.</i>

01:16:47.026 --> 01:16:49.295
<i>Almost.</i>

01:17:00.072 --> 01:17:01.939
<i>Four queens.</i>

01:17:01.941 --> 01:17:03.775
<i>The Village People.</i>

01:17:03.777 --> 01:17:07.247
(foreign language)

01:17:18.791 --> 01:17:20.824
(lighter flicks open)

01:17:20.826 --> 01:17:23.427
LAWRENCE (narrating): <i>Con
men don't play games.</i>

01:17:23.429 --> 01:17:25.698
<i>They play people.</i>

01:17:27.232 --> 01:17:30.168
<i>And people are unpredictable.</i>

01:17:30.170 --> 01:17:35.172
To be honest with you,
they were happier times.

01:17:35.174 --> 01:17:37.744
Salad days. (chuckles)

01:17:39.946 --> 01:17:42.649
I remember them with affection.

01:17:44.384 --> 01:17:46.519
I remember differently.

01:17:49.822 --> 01:17:53.423
You've done a really good
job with Sarah, you know.

01:17:53.425 --> 01:17:58.895
She's a beautiful woman,
just like her mother.

01:17:58.897 --> 01:18:01.900
Though she has my eyes.

01:18:06.205 --> 01:18:10.106
She's nothing like her mother.

01:18:10.108 --> 01:18:12.877
Really?

01:18:12.879 --> 01:18:17.916
When she finds a man who gives
her what you can't, she's gone.

01:18:30.263 --> 01:18:32.732
ALICE: Hey!

01:18:35.567 --> 01:18:39.805
It's only cheating when you
get caught, right, Professor?

01:18:41.073 --> 01:18:43.442
ALICE: Get him out of here.

01:18:51.651 --> 01:18:55.521
I trust that no one else
will insult the house.

01:18:58.090 --> 01:19:00.892
She left me too, you know.

01:19:01.995 --> 01:19:04.361
I suppose I shouldn't be surprised.

01:19:04.363 --> 01:19:06.564
I was the card player,

01:19:06.566 --> 01:19:09.035
but she was a better liar.

01:19:14.072 --> 01:19:17.776
What are you doing here, kid?

01:19:20.379 --> 01:19:23.213
I mean, really,

01:19:23.215 --> 01:19:26.518
what the hell are you doing here?

01:19:40.566 --> 01:19:42.969
You sure about that?

01:19:45.204 --> 01:19:48.172
(chuckling)

01:19:48.174 --> 01:19:50.675
Yes. Don't feel bad.

01:19:50.677 --> 01:19:52.944
Honesty.

01:19:52.946 --> 01:19:55.081
It's a good quality.

01:20:11.397 --> 01:20:13.599
(exhales)

01:20:15.535 --> 01:20:18.468
You little fuck!

01:20:18.470 --> 01:20:19.906
(grunts)

01:20:28.447 --> 01:20:33.050
<i>♪ Mmm, mmm, yeah, yeah, yeah ♪</i>

01:20:33.052 --> 01:20:37.357
<i>♪ Oh, ah ♪</i>

01:20:43.562 --> 01:20:50.001
<i>♪♪ (vocalizing)</i>

01:20:52.170 --> 01:20:56.172
<i>♪ Whoa, yeah ♪</i>

01:20:56.174 --> 01:20:59.543
<i>♪ Yeah, yeah, yeah ♪♪</i>

01:20:59.545 --> 01:21:02.346
<i>♪♪ (man rapping on radio)</i>

01:21:02.348 --> 01:21:05.418
- <i>♪♪ (stops)</i>
- (sighs)

01:21:07.085 --> 01:21:09.086
I can't do this.

01:21:09.088 --> 01:21:11.090
It's our only chance.

01:21:17.263 --> 01:21:20.398
I wrote a letter.

01:21:20.400 --> 01:21:22.567
I should take it in.

01:21:25.103 --> 01:21:27.005
I'll do it.

01:21:31.710 --> 01:21:34.679
Back in a minute.

01:22:00.807 --> 01:22:03.742
- She finally did it.
- Shit!

01:22:05.344 --> 01:22:08.412
My little girl's grown up.

01:22:08.414 --> 01:22:11.148
She's on her own. Good girl.

01:22:11.150 --> 01:22:12.650
Not on her own.

01:22:12.652 --> 01:22:15.485
We planned it together.

01:22:15.487 --> 01:22:20.291
This note, it's for you.

01:22:20.293 --> 01:22:23.427
I think you'll find, my dear boy,

01:22:23.429 --> 01:22:25.465
it's for you.

01:22:45.418 --> 01:22:47.383
LAWRENCE (narrating):
<i>In a sweetheart con,</i>

01:22:47.385 --> 01:22:50.253
<i>the suckers rope themselves.</i>

01:22:50.255 --> 01:22:53.925
Listen, anyway, we've
got your wallet, so...

01:22:56.495 --> 01:22:59.197
To no fucking friends at all.

01:23:00.500 --> 01:23:03.434
We can do this, Lawrence.

01:23:03.436 --> 01:23:05.938
We have to. We can leave him.

01:23:09.674 --> 01:23:12.810
I wrote a letter.

01:23:12.812 --> 01:23:15.747
I should take it in.

01:23:19.384 --> 01:23:21.252
SARAH'S VOICE: <i>I'm sorry
for leaving like this,</i>

01:23:21.254 --> 01:23:23.319
<i>but it's all I know how to do.</i>

01:23:23.321 --> 01:23:26.222
<i>I can imagine how you'll feel,</i>

01:23:26.224 --> 01:23:28.324
<i>but I just couldn't face good-bye.</i>

01:23:28.326 --> 01:23:30.493
<i>Not with you.</i>

01:23:30.495 --> 01:23:33.663
<i>You know what they
say... "lucky at cards."</i>

01:23:33.665 --> 01:23:35.498
<i>(chuckles)</i>

01:23:35.500 --> 01:23:38.836
<i>Thank you for everything.</i>

01:23:38.838 --> 01:23:41.504
<i>Say good-bye to him for me.</i>

01:23:41.506 --> 01:23:44.475
"I will miss you and think of you often.

01:23:44.477 --> 01:23:47.647
Love always, Sarah."

01:23:56.455 --> 01:24:00.724
You were great out there tonight, my boy.

01:24:00.726 --> 01:24:02.961
You're a real player.

01:24:04.429 --> 01:24:06.462
- I let the team down.
- But...

01:24:06.464 --> 01:24:09.699
The better man won.

01:24:09.701 --> 01:24:11.467
Aren't you angry?

01:24:11.469 --> 01:24:15.538
(sighs) I'd have given
it to her if she'd asked.

01:24:15.540 --> 01:24:17.576
It's only money.

01:24:18.945 --> 01:24:22.279
Mine's a dying art, my boy.

01:24:22.281 --> 01:24:25.916
An art of grace and tact.

01:24:25.918 --> 01:24:30.221
Nowadays, a chap in a suit
can hit some keys in a machine

01:24:30.223 --> 01:24:31.955
and rob honest people of millions

01:24:31.957 --> 01:24:34.326
without even lookin' 'em in the eye.

01:24:35.628 --> 01:24:38.828
We trick people into giving us money.

01:24:38.830 --> 01:24:41.931
We make them dishonest.

01:24:41.933 --> 01:24:45.502
They're dishonest to begin with.

01:24:45.504 --> 01:24:47.773
Even you.

01:25:10.263 --> 01:25:12.629
Chinese lucky money?

01:25:12.631 --> 01:25:14.297
You might need it.

01:25:14.299 --> 01:25:17.267
How about you?

01:25:17.269 --> 01:25:19.638
I'll be fine.

01:25:23.808 --> 01:25:27.711
You saw it coming, right? This is
a con movie, you said to yourself,

01:25:27.713 --> 01:25:30.681
and all con movies end with a scam.

01:25:30.683 --> 01:25:32.416
Well, you're right.

01:25:32.418 --> 01:25:34.651
But even though it does end with a scam,

01:25:34.653 --> 01:25:36.654
this isn't a con movie.

01:25:36.656 --> 01:25:38.721
This is my life.

01:25:38.723 --> 01:25:40.759
(voices rewinding)

01:25:46.064 --> 01:25:50.700
(breathing deeply) I can't do this.

01:25:50.702 --> 01:25:53.870
- Sarah, listen...
- No, Lawrence, you don't understand.

01:25:53.872 --> 01:25:57.076
I was going to leave you both.

01:25:59.344 --> 01:26:02.346
I'm sorry.

01:26:02.348 --> 01:26:05.017
I didn't know what to do.

01:26:15.594 --> 01:26:17.260
Sarah.

01:26:17.262 --> 01:26:21.998
Children grow up and leave their
parents. It's what's supposed to happen.

01:26:22.000 --> 01:26:25.271
He just needs to know
he's been a father to you.

01:26:27.439 --> 01:26:30.976
(inhales, exhales)

01:26:32.445 --> 01:26:35.546
But what about you?

01:26:35.548 --> 01:26:38.015
You're the only friend I've ever had.

01:26:38.017 --> 01:26:40.484
LAWRENCE (narrating): <i>Some
things are not quite lies</i>

01:26:40.486 --> 01:26:43.921
<i>and not quite truth.</i>

01:26:43.923 --> 01:26:46.726
I'll be okay.

01:26:48.960 --> 01:26:51.763
<i>They're just what
people need to hear.</i>

01:26:53.031 --> 01:26:55.099
PROFESSOR: <i>"I'm sorry
for leaving like this,</i>

01:26:55.101 --> 01:26:58.403
<i>but it's all I know how to do.</i>

01:27:01.107 --> 01:27:03.774
I can imagine how you will feel,

01:27:03.776 --> 01:27:06.510
but I just couldn't face good-bye.

01:27:06.512 --> 01:27:09.113
Not... Not with you.

01:27:09.115 --> 01:27:15.054
You know what they say... 'lucky at cards.'

01:27:16.955 --> 01:27:19.324
Thank you for everything.

01:27:20.492 --> 01:27:23.092
Say good-bye to him for me.

01:27:23.094 --> 01:27:26.096
I will miss you

01:27:26.098 --> 01:27:28.399
and think of you often.

01:27:28.401 --> 01:27:31.036
Love always, Sarah."

01:27:36.075 --> 01:27:39.943
You were great out there tonight, my boy.

01:27:39.945 --> 01:27:42.111
A real player.

01:27:42.113 --> 01:27:44.715
- I let the team down.
- But...

01:27:44.717 --> 01:27:46.883
No, the better man won.

01:27:46.885 --> 01:27:48.851
No.

01:27:48.853 --> 01:27:52.422
